<FIRST>r a PM-HarvardTrademark     12-29 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Harvard Trademark,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Question Is: Will They Spell It Hahvud?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLISON J. PUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harvard University, whose name has been
emblazoned on sweatshirts from Los Angeles to Maine as well as on
shot glasses, towels, watches and boxer shorts, has decided to make
the name a trademark.
   Under new licensing procedures, Crimson-themed boxer shorts may
still be allowed. But string bikinis? Maybe not.
   Licensing will protect Harvard name, according to Ellen Mitchell
of the Harvard Office of Patents, Copyrights and Licensing.
   ``We just don't want it to be outrageous,'' she said. ``We don't
want to look silly.''
   More than 100 U.S. colleges and universities already issue
licenses for the use of their name, including the seven other Ivy
League colleges, according to the office of Robert Scott, vice
president for finance.
   Margot Naulleau, international licensing coordinator for
Champion Products Inc., one of the main suppliers of athletic wear
with college insignias, said Harvard was one of the last big
schools in the country to issue a trademark.
   But Harvard officials had a good explanation.
   ``It's simply that we are very old and very conservative. It
took us a long time to decide if it was something that we ought to
do,'' said Joyce Brinton, director of the patent office. She said
there was no incident that led to the decision to apply for a
trademark, such as a particularly egregious product on the market.
   ``It was just that the time has come,'' she said.
   Before the Harvard Corporation decided in June to apply for a
trademark on the name from the U.S. Patent and Trademarking Office,
Brinton's office had ``inquiries from many, many manufacturers''
about getting a license.
   ``I think most of the companies have felt uncomfortable that
they don't have a license from Harvard,'' said Brinton. Those
companies worried that if they didn't have a license, they ran the
risk of being left with hundreds of products if the school's
lawyers suddenly cracked down on the name's usage, she said.
   Harvard ran a few trial programs before moving towards licensing
on a broad scale. At the school's 350th anniversary in 1986,
Harvard wanted to ensure commemorative items were of high quality.
Another program licensing the trademark in Japan has been booming,
bringing in $130,000 in royalties annually.
   Under the new licensing procedure, if someone wants to make a
product bearing the name Harvard, Harvard University, or the
school's insignia, they must first show designs and samples to
demonstrate the quality of the product before Harvard will grant a
license.
   And the cost of renting the Harvard name? A bargain, Mitchell
said. Brinton said companies that market Harvard products pay a
flat fee of $300 and sales royalties of 7{ percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891229-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-29-89 0538EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Eastern     12-29 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Cuts 600 Jobs, Trims 10,000 Salaries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines plans 600 more layoffs along with
salary cuts for half its employees under measures to stem the flood
of red ink that has swamped the airline for a decade.
   About 10,000 workers will have wages temporarily slashed from 10
percent to 20 percent, although some of those cuts must be
negotiated with the Air Line Pilots Association and the flight
attendants union.
   The principal cause of the cuts _ which were announced Thursday
_ is the sale of Eastern's Latin American routes to American
Airlines.
   But Tom Matthews, Eastern's senior vice president for human
resources, also cited ``the softness in the economy ... the
increase in fuel prices, the extensive competition in the Miami
hub,'' particularly from Pan American World Airways.
   The package is expected to save $100 million next year for
Eastern, which reported a $185.2 million loss in this year's third
quarter.
   Eastern President Phil Bakes said pay and benefit reductions
were ``something we wanted to avoid,'' but that large losses are
expected to continue in the first half of the new year.
   The cuts are also part of Eastern's bankruptcy court plan for
financial reorganization that stemmed from the March 4 strike that
virtually idled the Miami-based carrier for weeks. Eastern claimed
it was losing $1 million a day prior to the strike.
   The majority of the layoffs will involve administrative and
airport service personnel, and will not include the unionized
pilots, flight attendants or mechanics.
   Attrition and early retirement will blunt the effects of the
cutbacks, but a number of operations-related employees will be out
of work Jan. 31 as Miami operations fall from 75 to 50 daily
flights.
   Job cuts also will come July 1 when American Airlines is
scheduled to assume the Latin routes.
   Meanwhile, half of Eastern's 20,000 employees _ including
management, pilots and flight attendants working at the older,
higher wage levels _ will have their wages cut by 10 percent to 20
percent for a year, beginning Jan. 16.
   About 850 pilots will see their $72,000 salaries slashed by 20
percent for six months. Half of the cut will be restored after six
months, and wages are scheduled to return to normal after a year.
About 950 newly hired pilots are working for $27,500 a year and
will not be affected.
   Flight attendants earning a pre-strike salary of $30,000 a year
will take a 15 percent initial cut, but those hired under the new
wage levels of $15,000 will not.
   Machinists, who had cuts imposed when the strike began, aren't
affected. Machinists remain the only group that hasn't gone back to
work.
   Mary Jane Barry, head of Eastern's flight attendants union,
refused to comment on the proposal, saying negotiations were
continuing. Calls to ALPA were not returned.
   Eastern employed 32,000 before the strike began, and the airline
filed for bankruptcy protection five days later.
   Eastern, a Texas Air Corp. subsidiary, plans to reshape itself
with about 75 percent of its operations centered at Atlanta.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
