and are worried about layoffs in 1990, an informal call-in survey
sponsored by a job-counseling company found.
   About 600 of the 1,100 people who participated in the national
call-in were employed, and nearly half of that number, 44 percent,
felt 1990 would bring significant changes for them in the
workplace, the firm, Challenger, Gray &amp; Christmas, said Friday.
   The survey is not scientific because it was not a random
sampling of the population.
